'''Semantic templates''' are a method of including additional annotation mark-up into templates. This has several advantages:
*users specify annotations without learning any new syntax, *annotations are used consistently, i.e. users do not have to look for the right properties or categories when editing a page, *since templates also have other functions, such as rendering flashy infoboxes in an article, users are motivated to use them.
For these reasons, we recommend you use semantic templates when introducing semantics into a wiki. {{Copyright of article |own work=True |copyright holder=Ontoprise GmbH |year=2009 |date retrieved=2009/12/11 |answer=Semantic templates are a method of including additional annotation mark-up into templates |for_releases=all }} [[UME discourse state::EditWikisyntax| ]] [[UME discourse state::SpecialPages| ]] [[UME link::Help:Using templates to simplify annotations| ]] {{Content hash|value=}} {{Part of bundle|value=Smwusermanual}}

The '''ParserFunctions''' extension is a collection of parser functions (note the difference between the name of the collection, and the general term). These parser functions have a hash character in front of the function name, so they typically have this syntax: 

  <nowiki>{{#functionname|argument 1 | argument 2 | argument 3...</nowiki>}}

<br> The extension defines nine functions: '''expr&nbsp;''',&nbsp;'''if&nbsp;''',&nbsp;'''ifeq&nbsp;''',&nbsp;'''ifexist&nbsp;''',&nbsp;'''ifexpr&nbsp;''',&nbsp;'''switch&nbsp;''',&nbsp;'''time&nbsp;''',&nbsp;'''rel2abs&nbsp;''', and &nbsp;'''titleparts'''.

