Every wiki page has an associated talk page which can be used for discussion and communicating with other users.
Talk pages can be accessed by clicking the '''''Discussion'' '''tab at the top of the page. Simply '''edit''' the page as normal to&nbsp;'''add''' your comment.
A talk page is actually very similar to any other wiki page, but it is in the '''talk''' namespace, to keep it separate from the articles in the '''main'''&nbsp;namespace&nbsp;&nbsp;As with any wiki page, you can edit it, link to it, and view the editing history. {{Copyright of article |own work=True |copyright holder=Ontoprise GmbH |year=2009 |date retrieved=2009/11/10 |answer=Every wiki page has an associated Talk page which can be used for discussion and communicating with other users |for_releases=all }} [[UME discourse state::General| ]] [[UME link::Help:Using talk pages| ]] {{Content hash|value=}} {{Part of bundle|value=Smwusermanual}}

A concept is a page in the '''Concept: namespace''' that is always described by a semantic query.

For example, the [http://semanticweb.org/wiki/Concept:Semantic_Web_events_2008 Concept:Semantic Web events 2008] page describes certain events in 2008. 

Its concept page contains the following text which enables it to fulfill this function:

<pre><nowiki>
{{#concept:  [[Category:Event]] [[start date::> Jan 1 2008]] [[start date::< Dec 31 2008]] 
| Events in the year 2008 that have been announced on semanticweb.org. 
  To add more events, go to the page "Events" on semanticweb.org.
}}
</nowiki></pre>

